{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"64881ca5-09eb-4584-81d6-95c9766c733c","content":"Here's my analysis:\n\n**Root Cause:** Every `dotnet build` invocation cold-starts a new MSBuild process — JIT, SDK resolution, project evaluation — even when nothing changed. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping MSBuild resident in-process.\n\nThe `.csproj` itself is already clean and minimal. The fix is workflow/environment configuration, not project changes.\n\n### Recommendations (ordered by impact)\n\n**1. Enable the MSBuild Server (biggest win)**\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\nKeeps an MSBuild server process alive between builds, eliminating JIT and startup overhead on subsequent invocations. Add it to your shell profile (`.bashrc`, `.zshrc`, etc.).\n\n**2. Ensure MSBuild node reuse is enabled**\n```bash\n# Make sure this is NOT set to 1 in your environment:\nunset MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE\n```\nNode reuse lets MSBuild worker nodes persist between builds. Some CI templates disable this — verify it's not leaking into your dev environment.\n\n**3. Use `dotnet watch` for inner-loop cycles**\n```bash\ndotnet watch run          # rebuilds + runs on save\ndotnet watch build        # rebuilds on save (no run)\n```\nThis keeps the process alive continuously — no repeated startup cost at all. Best option for rapid edit-build-test cycles.\n\n**4. Use the terminal logger for faster feedback**\n```bash\ndotnet build --tl\n```\nThe terminal logger (`--tl`) gives a streamlined live view and reduces console I/O overhead.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The project is fine — the bottleneck is MSBuild process startup on every CLI invocation. Enable the MSBuild server (`DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`) for the quickest win, and adopt `dotnet watch` for the best inner-loop experience.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3bad5b33-7e46-4dea-b98d-ab0361564e63","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer report describes a common issue: `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds compared to Visual Studio. The key insight from the report is:\n\n> The overhead seems to come from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation.\n\nThis is a well-known issue. Visual Studio keeps an MSBuild server process running (it hosts MSBuild in-process), so it avoids the JIT and project re-evaluation overhead on each build. The CLI, by default, starts a new MSBuild process each time.\n\nThe solutions are:\n\n1. **Use the MSBuild Server (`-nodeReuse:true` / MSBuild Server)**: .NET 8+ includes an MSBuild server that keeps the MSBuild process alive between builds, similar to what Visual Studio does. This can be enabled with the environment variable `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` or by using the `--tl` (terminal logger) flag. Actually, let me be more precise.\n\n\n2. **Use `dotnet build-server`**: In .NET 8+, there's an MSBuild server that can be reused between builds. The key property is `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`.\n3. **Use `dotnet watch`**: For edit-build-test cycles, `dotnet watch` keeps the process alive and rebuilds on file changes.\n4. **Graph-based builds with `-graph`**: Using `dotnet build -graph` can help with multi-project solutions by doing a static graph evaluation.\n5. **Enable MSBuild node reuse**: Set `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE` to false to allow MSBuild to reuse nodes across invocations.\n\nThe real bottleneck is that each `dotnet build` call starts fresh—spinning up the CLI, JITting MSBuild, re-evaluating projects, and checking targets. Visual Studio sidesteps this by keeping MSBuild in-process. The biggest win is enabling the MSBuild server in .NET 8+, which maintains a persistent server between builds and eliminates startup and JIT overhead. For development workflows, `dotnet watch` is also valuable since it keeps the process running and only rebuilds when files change. dotnet watch` for continuous rebuilds, and making sure `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE` isn't set to `1` to allow node reuse. The `.csproj` is already clean, so the real gains come from how the build is being invoked rather than project configuration changes.","outputTokens":1472,"requestId":"4430:262AAE:17FEE10:1B140F3:69FE8585"},"id":"dfc0de39-5f2c-4f7e-9928-7ddd393386f5","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:53:57.810Z","parentId":"4f4b1c7c-2faf-4c1b-a9cb-a61c9c79e787"}
